    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "That's a good start for the intro. I also wanted to make sure they understand why it's so important compared to just 'procedural due process.' Could you add a section explaining why the procedural side isn't enough to actually protect people's fundamental rights? Like, why relying on just the 'how' of the law fails to protect the actual 'what' of their rights?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Substantive due process is not just about the 'how' of the law; it's about the 'what' that truly matters. Procedural due process is like a safety net that ensures fair procedures, but it doesn't always protect the core rights that make us human. It's like having a referee in a game, but not caring about the players' health or safety. Substantive due process steps in to make sure that the rules of the game don't trample on our basic freedoms, like speech, privacy, and equality. It's the difference between having a fair trial and having a fair society. Without substantive due process, procedural due process alone would be like having a referee who doesn't care if the players are getting hit in the face. It's not enough to just follow the rules; we need to make sure those rules don't harm our fundamental rights. Substantive due process is the guardian of our deepest values, ensuring that the Constitution's promise of justice and equality isn't just a nice idea, but a lived reality for all. It's the difference between a society that respects individual liberties and one that just goes through the motions. So, let's not just play by the rules; let's make sure those rules protect what really matters. Substantive due process",
      "source": "target",
